To evaluate the analytical performance of ultra-small CDs for assaying of Cu2+ ion, the solutions of ultra-small CDs were treated separately with different concentrations of Cu2+ ion (0.01–500 μM) (Fig. 4
                        a). It can be observed that the fluorescence emission peak at 468 nm concomitantly decreases with increasing concentration of Cu2+ ion. As a result, the fluorescence quenching efficiency (I0/I) was proportional to the concentration of Cu2+ ion, resulting a good linearity with correlation coefficient (R2
                        ) of 0.9907 for Cu2+ ion between values of I0/I and Cu2+ ion concentration in the range of 0.01–10 μM (Fig. 4b). The limit of detection is 4.3 nM (3σ/k), which is lower than that of other fluorescent (gold nanoclusters (Au NCs), QDs and CDs) and colorimetric sensors (gold and silver nanoparticles (Au and Ag NPs)) for Cu2+ ion [31–48] (Table 1
                        ). Importantly, the obtained LOD is quite lower than the WHO recommendation for Cu2+ ion in drinking water, which reveals that the potentiality of ultra-small CDs for assaying of Cu2+ ion.
